# Workspace tool INVENTORY — one row per tool:  <source>  <command>  [agent note]
#   col 1   install source: a mise package name (installed via `mise use -g`), or `-`
#           for a tool present by other means (base image, another setup step) — a `-`
#           row is NOT installed, only (optionally) advertised.
#   col 2   command name; advertised only if it passes `command -v`, so the note can
#           never claim an absent tool.
#   col 3+  agent-facing note. PRESENT => advertised as a bullet in the session context;
#           ABSENT => silent (installed/present but not worth agent context, e.g. a
#           human-only tool). The installer never reads this column.
# The two axes are independent: col1 decides install, col3 decides advertisement — so a
# base-image tool advertises without installing (`- docker  Docker CLI …`) and a
# human-only tool installs without advertising (`bat  bat`, no note).
#
# The installer + advertiser read the UNION of every /opt/toolchain/tools.d/*.list, so
# add tools by shipping ANOTHER fragment (no need to copy this one); blank lines and
# #-comments are ignored. If one command appears in two fragments with different col1,
# the advertiser keeps the first-seen note and the installer still installs any mise row.
# A pack that provisions tools outside mise either adds `-` rows here or ships its own
# session-context.d fragment.
#
# Deliberately lean + generic — a profile adds its own kit via a fragment
# (see overlay/50-example/tools.d/extras.list for an example).
uv          uv        Python envs/deps/run (prefer over pip & venv)
github-cli  gh        GitHub CLI — PRs, issues, API
ripgrep     rg        ripgrep — fast content search
fd          fd        fast file find (prefer over find)
